title: Works well for me
text:
*Update*
I've changed my detergent and no longer see any residue after washing. I am loving this thing. It was a great purchase. I still stand by everything in my review as far as the capacity for regular dishes and regular use, but if you have a very little amount of dishes and keep up with it, you'll love the convenience. Also, if you're into canning, it fits an impressive amount of jars.

*Original*
I'm not entirely sure this purchase was necessary, but I'm enjoying my new toy. I live by myself and work about 13-15 hrs per day 6 days a week so, I'm not home much to create too many dishes. But, the few dishes I do dirty up tend to sit (rinsed) in the sink for a few days before I get the time or energy to wash them. So far, it's been really nice to just rinse and shove in the dishwasher until there's enough to run it. I also really love that I don't have to install it with a water line. It takes a very small amount of water ( I think under a gallon and a half) so it's definitely less than I would use hand washing. I have a very small kitchen, and I like that the footprint is reasonably small. I love that it heats the water internally and has a top and bottom sprayer, as well as a dry program. I had one in my cart that was only $50 cheaper and didn't have a top sprayer, heater, or dry function. I'm really glad I searched around a bit, because I think that $50 extra was well spent. I have noticed that my dishes tend to come out with a bit of a film that I have to polish off, which is why I'm not sure it's quite the time saver I was hoping it would be. Maybe I should just switch my detergent. I've seen reviews where they pile WAY more inside than I do and rave about the cleanliness of the dishes when they come out, so I'm a little confused at that. From my experience, you need to be very careful to position your dishes so the water can actually hit them.

Be aware, it's still just a small dishwasher. It's not a magic portal that zaps food particles into the ether. You will still need to rinse your dishes after using them. I work in a professional kitchen and even our commercial dishwasher isn't that magical. I think this product is for a niche market and will work well for some, but may not suit the average household. Overall, I'm happy. It works very well for my living situation.

title: OK, not great
text:
I bought the induction cooktop while it was on sale, just to try it out (after seeing demos on Cook's Illustrated). The biggest concern with all induction cooktops is that you must have the right cookware, but here I wanted to focus on what may be unique to this cooktop (versus others you might get).

PROS: Very fast at bringing pots and pans to temperature (for example, I can boil water in about 2 minutes using this cooktop, and it takes about 5 minutes on my electric stove), and fast at temperature control. There are also some nice safety features.

CONS: This does not have a continuous temp control, but 6 temps- I found that many times I need a slow simmer, but one temp was too high, and the next one down was too low. Another issue with low temps is that there is not a continuous low temp- The temperature pulses on and off. One annoyance (common or not?) is that when you lift a pan off the cooktop, it automatically gives a warning and shuts off.

Conclusions for me: Nice for occasional use, but not a complete replacement for electric or gas.

text:
My washing machine broke at the start of the recent quarantine, and I'm still waiting for an appointment to have it fixed. With most laundromats closed, in desperation I bought a Wonderwash, hoping it would tide me over until I can get my washing machine fixed.

This little machine is great! It is well-made and all the parts feel sturdy and high-quality. It arrives unassembled but is a breeze to put together, it takes five minutes and no tools. I highly recommend watching one of the instructional Youtube videos before doing your first load of wash, it explains the process thoroughly, but the basics are: determine load size, add a small amount of detergent and fill with hot or warm water to the fill line. Add clothes, tighten down the lid, then just turn the crank for two minutes or so (I time it by listening to a song on the radio.)

The key is to turn the crank slowly, not quickly, and let the wet laundry fall from the top of the chamber to the bottom with a good thud each time. This drives the water and soap through the clothes and cleans them thoroughly. Once you're done, drain the chamber using the supplied pipe, then refill with cool water to the fill line and crank for two minutes again to rinse.

My clothes came out really clean! Even garments with cooking stains washed right up. The only drawbacks are that water tends to splatter around a bit when you drain the chamber, and I found that to drain it completely when I was done I needed to turn the whole chamber upside down and let it set for a bit. I use the Wonderwash in my bathtub, so a little bit of water splashing around is not an issue.

Other than that, this is a perfect little machine for doing small loads of laundry. It was a desperation buy, but I am really pleased with it! After my main washer is fixed, I intend to keep it to use in my RV camper. It would also be great for dorm or apartment dwellers.

title: Love this! Excellent dishwasher. Tips..
text:
Looks sleek. Quiet. Dishes clean in about an hour. Fits on counters. Love having it!

Just be sure to use soap pods vs liquid. The latter doesn't work and makes a mess. And sometimes the pods don't quite fully dissolve either, as common to dishwashers. The workaround is placing them right in the bottom of the dishwasher, gel side down so they dissolve first as designed. Yes, this works fine! It never leaves soap streaks or a missed pod discharge where it sits on dishes turning gooey and not cleaning the whole lot.

Also, no, you can't jam as much as possible into this thing like standard dishwashers. You really must be reasonable and leave some gaps for everything to get clean. Otherwise you'll have to re-do them. I've learned ;)

Got oversized plates? My big plates technically don't fit but I manage to lean them over more on one end and it works out. Or hand wash. Small and medium pots fit with little else, but large pots not so well.

I disagree with one design element… The cutlery basket. It's too big! And by that, takes up too much valuable real estate. After months of use, I got rid of the basket, and bought a mesh pen holder on Amazon and use that instead. It's a smaller footprint and gives way more space for dishes. If you have extra cutlery you can always lay it down.

Any hardware store it was exactly what you mean if you walk in and say you need a dishwasher converter hook up for your faucet.

Only con: I have no idea what such a beautiful portable dishwashers don't also come with a simple cheap rubber to that would run from the faucet device down into the bottom of your sink basin or drain hole. Instead it splashes at full force from your spout into the sink which doesn't make some noise. This bugged me so at the hardware store I found they sell Liston blue tubing by the foot in the plumbing section. It's cheap, and I just use a potato chip bag clip to fix it onto the white Fossett thingy, and now the water runs quietly through that right into my garbage disposal. It would cost so little to provide, and makes a world of difference and eliminating splashing, and reducing the sound almost nothing.

The other con is even though you turn off the faucet when it's done, when you go to remove the white tubes from your faucet, the residual pressure does kind of create a splash of water (I have great water pressure), so I use a washcloth to contain it when I remove it.

Overall yeah it's a couple steps to hook it up, but it becomes 2nd nature, and it's sooo worth not having to do dishes!

* Which settings to use for different cleaning tasks.
* How to silence the beep after the load is done.

* When, how to use the Sanitize setting (short answer: it also promotes better dish drying, so use it regularly).
* How to optimally load the system before washing.
* How to periodically check the rotary arms and the filters as recommended in the manual. (So far, only the filters have required occasional rinse out, in my own experience.)

This model was an upgrade from what my local appliance retailer normally stocks, but I chose it for its multi-level filtration and other upgrade features: figuring that, for a few bucks more, you install it, then you live with your choice almost every day of your life for several years, so it makes sense to buy a good performer. This pressure seems to be why these splash shields fail so often.  Since these don't flex as well as the originals, they are prone to be dislodged when the rack rolls over them.  This can cause leakage.  It can also cause the shields to fail even sooner since they don't flex as well.  As a matter of interest, I recently checked the current models of the Whirlpool, etc. dishwashers and they don't use this splash shield at all but have redesigned the door and the door seal. title: Consider getting a transparent hose
text:
Is this a dishwasher hose or a clothes-washing machine hose? It seems targeted at both since it has the bracket for a washing machine and the universal end for a dishwasher. Both hose types are essentially the same as long as they fit. This product is more suitable for a washing machine than a dishwasher, but it should work for both.

This is a fine dishwasher hose that you can cut to the right exit diameter. In addition to the exit diameter, make sure the end will fit as there are L-shaped and straight ends. For going into the garbage disposal, having a straight end at that location reduces clogging. Confirm the length you need. If you need to wrap the hose over the top of the dishwasher to get to the drain then 6 ft will not be long enough. This comes with two smaller clamps and one larger clamp, in addition to the extension connector and a hose holder if this is used with a clothes washing machine. For a washing machine, 6ft should be fine.

I have done a lot of dishwasher troubleshooting as a manager of rental properties. Most dishwasher drain hoses I encounter are somewhat transparent. I can see water and debris flowing through them and can see accumulated debris. This is useful when troubleshooting a drainage issue or investigating a possible clog. While not essential, since transparent hoses are so readily available, why not get one of those instead of this opaque one? The transparent ones are the hazy white-colored one that allows light through. I have never had a washing machine drain clog, so for that this opaque color is fine.

This is a generic Chinese hose and the identical product is being sold under different Amazon listings.

title: Fits into LG LFXS30766S
text:
My LG LFXS30766S refrigerator was icing up in the refrigerator compartment behind the bottom drawer. One symptom was that the drain hole iced over, so when the defrost the water could not get into the bottom evaporator pan and I would have pooled water in the refrigerator, where it would eventually freeze.

I initially solved the clogging issue with a short copper wire. I had some scraps of electrical wire that I stripped off the coating and wrapped it around the defrost line and had the wire extend down into the drain hole. A YouTube video shows how this works. The concept is the defrost line heats up and the heat extends to the copper wire in the drain hole. This copper wire trick worked.

While searching for a solution I came across these drain clips and I figured they would work even better due to the larger surface area. The next time I had to work on my refrigerator I pushed the copper wire aside and attached this clip. I had to bend the tip so the tip was not touching the plastic drain tube. These are made for a Samsung, but they work fine in an LG, and are easier to install than a copper wire because the clip right to the defrost line instead of having to be wrapped around with pliers. I bought two of these in case I have to install the same thing in the freezer compartment, or in case I need to solve this same problem in another refrigerator.

An earlier clog with similar symptoms was caused by hard water deposits clogging the bottom of the drain tube, where it touches the evaporator pan in the back. I fixed this by cutting off the bottom of the drain tube to leave a gap between the drain tube and the pan.

My refrigerator was still icing over after the copper wire fix, although the problem of water not draining was addressed. I am swapping a replacement defrost sensor next to see if that helps, which is why I had the back off to install this drain clip.

title: If your machine is growling, it's not the filter's fault.
text:
The filter works really well, especially compared to the one (at work) that no one had replaced in over a year. The coffee tastes much better!

Make sure that the reservoir is empty when you replace the filter, and prime the filter by rinsing under running water, and do a couple of brews without coffee before you get going with the actual coffee.

This next part is just my own misadventure and in no way the fault of these filters, but if I'm dumb enough to do it, I'm sure others will, too. I hope it helps other to "fix" their machines.

Our particular model has what is basically an inverted cup under the filter, meant to hold the filter and its handle in place. Our first error was replacing the filter while the reservoir was filled. The upside down "cup" forced a bubble of air into the pump, making it growl and barely function. Wondering what was wrong, we took everything apart, then did the same thing again, forcing even more air into the pump and making it not function at all, and growl horribly. (This is all at 8 AM, at work, pre- coffee. Imagine zombie monkies trying to troubleshoot while in acute caffeine withdrawal.) We really though it was broken.

God bless my coworker for his tenacity. He Googled the problem, and evidently the definitely-not-in-the-user-manual solution is to unplug the machine, remove the reservoir, and shake the machine violently. Act like it owes you money. Keep shaking. You are getting the air out of the pump.

Reassemble, plug in, refill the reservoir.

And here is where I figured out the whole "inverted cup of air" thing. I added the filter, again, and it started growing, again. My coworker disassembled, shook, reassembled and (understandably) yelled at me for trying to put the filter back in (because it always growled/got worse when I added the filter). This time I was looking for the air bubble and found it. I could have dumped the reservoir, added the filter, and refilled the reservoir - like an adult - but I just manipulated the filter housing to get the bubble out and went from there.

Normal function restored, caffeine withdrawal postponed. And the coffee tastes better, now!

title: You can make it work
text:
The description says it can be expanded to 29.5 inches (75cm) but if you do that, the aluminum bars holding it to the corners will have less than 1 inch of the bar inside of each end. This is not enough to hold 440 lbs. I would say that 30 lbs at full extension is about all it will hold up. The only way it will hold 440 lbs is when the unit is fully collapsed and that size was too small for my refrigerator. The aluminum bars are 1-inch square bars that slide into the corner piece made of heavy-duty plastic and that snug connection gives the stand its strength. The aluminum bars are very very thin and upgrading the quality of the bars will give a lot of strength to the stand. As-is, this unit would not hold the Galanz refrigerator I have pictured.

I did modify the stand. First I threw away the cheap aluminum bars. I could bend them with my bare hands without much difficulty. Next, I went to a big box home improvement store and purchased a 1-inch square steel bar (which cost more than the stand). After cutting the steel bar to length and tapping them into the corner pieces, the strength became a lot more than 440 lbs.

Bottom line is that as described, the sturdiness of the stand reduces significantly as you expand the stand length and width. The specs must describe the stand when it's fully collapsed. With a little know-how, you can make this work better by upgrading the length and strength of the bars.

title: We had a whirlpool last 20 years and then upgraded to an HE machine thinking how wonderful with 4 children and 8-10 loads per we
text:
Not unlike many others in many post forums including this one - we discovered that our HE machine was not built to last ... We had a whirlpool last 20 years and then upgraded to an HE machine thinking how wonderful with 4 children and 8-10 loads per week ... Sadly, our LG Top Load that Consumer Reports actually ranked the #`1 top load machine in 2014 lasted only 3 years. Less water and washing more clothes with no agitator was the draw ... (4.3 cubic feet - with no agitator) The trade offs were not worth it! Washing cycle times in excess of 90-105 minutes plus our clothes really did not get that clean - even using pre-soak and extra rinse features ... Notice the uptick with increased market offerings of washing machine fragrance products? Downy and UnStoppables are filling need to make poorly washed HE clothes smell better! They are covering up the FACT that HE machines SIMPLY DO NOT CLEAN and RINSE as WELL as traditional AGITATOR MACHINES

Only Now that we are using a new washing machine - we cant believe what we were putting up with! Half washed clothes!

We began searching for to replace our HE machine when frustrated with the repairman's diagnosis and $600 repair bill we kicked it to the curb - our repairman said most people are displeased that clothes do not get as clean as they like and they ALL use too much soap which gums up the internal belt drives. He said using the recommended amount of Soap IS STILL TOO MUCH FOR THESE MACHINES - he said he used HALF of the recommended soap in his HE machine at home (teaspoon) and they use scented fragrance to help their clothes smell better.

Spent hours scouring online reviews and feedback forums before settling on the Speed Queen AWNE82P ... found local dealer and brought home same day... Not amazed to learn our salesman has had the same machine for 14 years - deal made for $759 - straight of the box this machine was washing full loads in 27 minutes without extra rise. HE function does allow for HE soap to be used with machine using less water - but we prefer using regular soap and normal wash function. Clothes are rinsed out very well and are amazingly clean over what we got from our LG.

The basic standard warranty is 5 years parts and labor! What HE machine offers that? No one does... If you want a no frills made in America solid state product - this is the machine to buy ... We actually shove our faces in the towels to smell them again when pulling them out of the dryer!

title: My prefered brand is LG, this fridge has just one problem
text:
I like the way this fridge looks, and like all stainless appliances it shows streaks and finger prints, but it's worth it to me. If you are troubeled by that issue, don't by anything stainless. That isn't LGs fault, it's just a fact of the finish. I like that I can easily place a half sheet pan on any shelf and the fact that there are four separate drawers. All fridges are warmest at the top, so store less perishiable things up there.

It doesn't make huge amounts of ice, and the cubes are really small, but I don't have a large family so it isn't a problem for me. What is a problem is the way the left door closes. It is easy to have the mullion not go into it's channel, leaving the door open about an inch. It's true that it will beep after a minute or so, but if you grabbed your lunch out of the fridge on your way out the door, it will just beep all day and the fridge will be about 50 degrees on your return. Because I have never owned a french door fridge, I don't know if any other manufacturers have this problem. Could be a challenge for all of them.

I wouldn't recommend this fridge if you have children getting in and out of it for the above reason. If I had it to do over again, I'd buy this same model, even with the mullion problem. I just keep my lunch behind the right hand door now.

title: Made in China. Outrageously overpriced! Check out "tube ice" makers.
text:
There are a plethora of countertop icemakers being sold by mostly Chinese companies on Amazon right now. They are all very similar, with a few differences. The one main difference with this one is that it makes “nugget ice” and set up “tube ice”. The other thing that is “different” about this one is that it is super crazy over-the-top overpriced right now. More on that in a moment.

Make sure you understand exactly what this icemaker can and cannot do. This icemaker does not keep the ice frozen. Once the basket is filled, the machine will turn off and if you do not remove the ice, it will simply melt and the water goes back down into the reservoir, at which time the machine will turn back on and start making more ice. The only way to keep the ice frozen is to remove it from the basket and place it into your own freezer. But keep in mind the ice will be “wet” and you will need to break it apart when you remove it from the freezer.

The listing shows that this icemaker can make 30 pounds of ice per day. That is a bit of a misnomer. The only way that it can do that is if you continually remove the ice from the basket day and night. I highly doubt that someone is going to be up at 3 o'clock in the morning removing ice from this ice machine.

You really want to make sure that you turn the ice machine off when it is not in use like at night, and on weekends if you're using it in an office. Because otherwise the machine will continually make ice… The ice will melt… And there were machine will make ice again. In a never- ending cycle.

This ice machine is made in China and probably being sold by Chinese company on Amazon, though they are using a US address. This icemaker is currently listed at 400 bucks. Currently there is an eighty dollar coupon that you will certainly want to click on if you purchase. But you can purchase “tube ice” countertop icemakers for well under 100 bucks. So unless you are just adamant about this particular machine, I highly recommend you look into the “tube ice countertop icemakers first.

title: Made in China.  Know what to expect before purchasing.
text:
I've used several similar ice machines. There are several things you need to know before you purchase this machine to make sure your expectations meet exactly what this machine offers.

First of all, this machine is not connected to water. You fill the reservoir, in the front. Once the water is low, you refill the reservoir.

The listing shows that this machine can make 33# of ice in a 24-hour period. That is only possible if you have someone removing the ice from the basket . . . 24-hous. . . day-and-night.

This machine does not keep the ice frozen. The ice empties into a basket in the front. If you do not remove the ice; it will melt and refreeze. If you want to keep the ice frozen, you must remove it from the basket. . . place it into a plastic bag or container. . .and place it into your freezer. Note that the ice will be “wet” so when you remove it from the freezer, you'll need to break it apart.

You should turn the machine off when not in use. Such as nights. Otherwise the machine will continue to make ice. . . the ice melts. . . and recycles making ice again and again.

When you clean the machine, you need to add some coffee machine cleaner powder (the type which is mostly citric acid). I use a bottle brush to clean the inside the best that I can. When you start the cleaning cycle, it will run the solution through the machine several times. You need to make sure you use fresh clean water and let it cycle a few times also.

This ice machine is Made in China and being sold by a Chinese company on Amazon. This machine makes 24 small cubes at a time. Other, similar machines, are offered which make nice cubes for under a hundred bucks. Some also have a timer so they turn-off at night.

The “not-so-great”:

Before I start to list these. . I have to say. . . and I hate to keep repeating this. . . but I have been using an Asko for over 20-years. So there are certainly “advantages” to Asko. . . but. . . to have to weigh the cost and everything else.

I didn't know this until I read the manual. . .but. . . each spray arm sprays separately. In other words, they don't all spray at one time. Kind of “odd”, but that's the way it works.

I'm assuming, due to each spray arm spraying separately, it takes a LONG time for this dishwasher to go through a cycle. I rinse all of my dishes first. Just a habit that I have done since I was a kid. But even with the “quick wash” it takes almost 1.5-hours. With a “regular” wash it's well over two-hours and pushing three.

This dishwasher does NOT heat the water. That's one thing I really liked about Asko it heated the water. But because the LG doesn't heat the water, you must keep your hot water heat to at least 120 degrees. That's a LOT hotter than you would have to keep it if you didn't have such a dishwasher. So though this dishwasher might be an “energy star” dishwasher. . . I don't know if they considered that you're going to have to keep your hot water heather much higher than if you didn't have such a dishwasher.

FYI. . . . This can all depend upon how far your hot water heater is from your dishwasher. . .but. . . I found out, after first use, that I needed to run the hot water in the sink until it was scalding hot before I started the dishwasher. Otherwise the water that was going into the dishwasher was not hot enough and so the results were poor.

Cleaning. . . . Hmmmm.. . .. this is a hard one. But personally, I don't really think that it cleans nearly as well as my Asko. Granted. . . . I rinse all of my dishes anyway, so I don't have any problems. But if I didn't rinse them, then I think that I would. But if you rinse. . . and if you load the dishwasher correctly.. . then I think you will be fine.

It uses a lot of rinse aid, even on the lowest setting.

In summery. . …. . .

This dishwasher is supposed to hold up to 14-place-settings. I find that hard to believe. Even as a single person, I run a load almost daily. . . but. . . .I really hate to wash dishes in the sink, so my motto is “if it can't go in the dishwasher. . . throw it away and find something that can!”. Hahaha So for me, it's easy to fill a dishwasher.

Overall.. .. . Even with the “not-so-great” things about this dishwasher. . . I'm happy with it. My electric bill and gas (hot water) bill are still quite “normal” running the dishwasher daily. Oh… . .and if you're not familiar with LG appliances. . . they “jingle” when the cycle is complete!

title: I'm not a professional, but I've found it useful and easy to use
text:
I'm not a HVAC professional, but I am a scientifically-minded home owner. I've been curious as to how different actions affect the humidity in our pool room, among other things. I have no idea if this meter is correctly calibrated or not, and the manual doesn't talk about how to check this or calibrate it. However, I strongly suspect this is more accurate than anything I currently have. I mainly used the meter to check how an action changed the humidity or temperature in a room, which it appeared to do just fine.

"The meter displays three different temperature points of the air surrounding the meter's sensor: ambient, wet bulb, and dew point." The meter has buttons that allow you to hold, save, and/or recall data. It also has a MIN MAX AVG function. The directions are brief but I was able to use all these functions without a problem. The meter is powered by 4 AAA batteries. There is a power on/off button, but the meter will also automatically turn off after 20 minutes. There is a button to turn on and off a display backlight. The meter has a belt clip.

The display was large enough to read easily. It quickly arrived at the reading (about 3-5 seconds to stabilize unless in an area of air movement). The meter is for indoor use only. The manual warns "To extend sensor life, keep the sensor's protective shutter closed whenever the meter is not in use." There are no further directions about this shutter, but I can't find one despite the picture. It's possible I'm overlooking the obvious, but perhaps the obvious is that there isn't one.

I'd recommend reading the reviews by professionals. From the description I read to decide to review this or not, I'd assumed it was around $75 and "of professional quality" rather than an actual professional meter. I'd normally have left this to in-that-profession reviewers as I have no way to compare this to similar meters on the market nor can I comment on if the pricing is reasonable. title: Easy Repair For A Very Common Issue
text:
If you're dryer fails to start or continues to run with the door open, then there's a very good chance that your dryer door switch has failed. More likely, the plastic tab that comes in contact with the door has broken off.

This is a common problem that can be fixed by anyone in under 15 minutes. If you've never tackled this repair before, a quick YouTube search can show you how to access the lid switch for your dryer & then install your replacement. Just make sure to UNPLUG your dryer first!!

I can't speak to the lifespan of this particular switch, but it's probably not as durable as the OEM part. However, the OEM part will be ridiculously overpriced for the same result. This particular part from Beaquicy is inexpensive enough that you can purchase two just to have a spare. And even then still not come near the cost of one OEM replacement.

I've been running the dryer with the new switch in place since mid-Feb (2021) & I've had no problems. So, overall, I would consider this a successful repair & would have no issue recommending this part.

title: Easy Fix Fix For Stripped Agitator
text:
If your washer agitator is spinning freely in BOTH directions, then it's not working as intended.

The agitator should spin freely clockwise, but should then lock in place when spun counterclockwise. If your unit has an agitator that is spinning freely counterclockwise, then most likely this is due to the "agitator dogs" being broken or worn out.

This kit provides a complete & easy repair that anyone can make in 15 minutes. However, if needed, there are plenty of YT repair vids that explain this process.

While these parts are not as beefy as the OEM parts, they will work fine to get your washer back up & running.

text: I am in the process of getting one house ready to sell and moving back to my favorite town. title: I heard that news story about "coming for your gas stoves" - let them try!
text: I have used pretty much every type of stove top, on occasion, that you can think of and gas is my preferred stove top.  Why? Specifically, there is NO substitute for gas when making candy that requires watching the temperature of that boiling, bubbling goo - electric stove tops will burn it 9 times out of 10.  So, now you know why I got THIS stove top was to set up my permanent outdoor kitchen.  I weighed the costs of having my awful electric stove top in my kitchen replaced with gas (meaning I have an all-electric home) and decided I would rather put together an outdoor kitchen instead as I do live where it is hot much longer than it is cool throughout the year).  My house is set up to where I have a really good place just steps from my indoor kitchen.  This was an easy, drop in stove top for the counter and the great thing is, I have a propane powered pizza oven as well as a charcoal grill - I am set up for the whole meal, whatever that might be!  I do also have an interesting sink set up as well so that I can fill pans with water and wash off all the dirty dishes outside. Recently, I purchased a multi-use microwave oven that bakes and air fries (as well as other things) and is large enough for a big turkey, so I made the decision to remove the big, clunky old stove/oven unit and replace it with an induction "stove" unit without having an oven as all I need is included in my multi-microwave.  The only thing that I had to deal with was having an electrician come in to remove the plug behind where the original stove/oven sat and use that to hard wire this induction unit for me.  What I love is that it is a flat surface and I also have a silicone mat that I put down on top of the burner section when not in use so not only does it stay cleaner when not in use, but the silicone mat provides some safety for the induction top (from getting cracked/broken).  Last, just recently I purchased a set of beautiful stainless steel pots/pans and they are such a joy to work with on this induction cooktop.  My outdoor, two burner induction stove has knobs and that's why I like this one - it's familiar and I am older and knobs are easier for me to use (or maybe just more comfortable using).  Oh, and I do love having 5 cooking areas!

title: So much nicer than the last one I had
text: My last mini-fridge was the type with one door, the freezer area a tiny part in the top of the one section.  Having a separate freezer section means it doesn't freeze over because I've opened the one door that causes room air to create all those ice crystals.  This one is a bit larger by about a foot taller, but it is still a nice, compact unit but even though it is small, it holds quite a bit for a small/compact refrigerator/freezer.  I have installed this in a small trailer (camping) that is older.  I've been working to upgrade the trailer and this was a GREAT update to what was in it before updating.  It's so much nicer to be able to stock the fridge before leaving on a camping trip with enough food/drink to last the entire trip.  The fridge cools/freezes perfectly as it should (I have a solar panel/2000w inverter system that works well with this refrigerator) so even when I'm not hooked to external power, the electrical system keeps it working.  Very happy with my camper's new, upgraded refrigerator.  This would work well for a college student's dorm room, an off-site construction office trailer, a man-cave, and an outdoor kitchen as well as other situations.

title: Who wants to do dishes by hand?
text: I have a small trailer for camping and I am so happy to have this small dishwasher that I can stow in the trailer!  It's a bit larger than is easy to stow, but I did find room for it and I'm quite happy that I did!  This small dishwasher holds more than you would think and the wash/rinse cycle does one heck of a job to clean the dishes.  I love that it does not require adding hot water - that the dishwasher can heat the water itself.  As for how it cleans - it does a very decent job though I suspect part of the reason is that for such a small space, the water jets can get to every part of the dirty dishes loaded on it!  The only thing I could wish for is that it weigh less - 30 pounds on something kind of large and bulky means I do wrestle with it when stowing it away and getting it back out to use it the next time.  Still, it does a great job of washing dishes!

title: This one is it!
text: I have been updating lots of things around my house - it is an old house and so many things needed updating.  The range hood that was in the house was on its last leg - it had a knob for selecting a level of exhaust (I'm assuming low-medium-high) and no matter which one I used, I got the same air/flow rate that also seemed...kind of clogged.  I did take out the filter and clean it, but that didn't seem to help.  I changed out the light bulb and it doesn't work so...time for it to go!  Replaced it with this beautiful stainless steel one (did I mention the old one was a cream enamel? So ugly!) - makes it easier when you already have a vented range hood so this was an easy install.  I absolutely love having lights again!  The stainless steel hood is just so clean and neat, too.

title: Updating my kitchen
text: I had one of those really ugly, very traditional range hoods that had seen better days and just needed to be tossed for a more useful, current and up-to-date range hood.  That meant THIS one for me!  It wasn't too difficult to install, especially since I already had a vent in that space.  The venting was already there in the proper place so it was truly not hard to install this one where the old one had been.  What I love are the push-button controls and LED lights instead of the old one's incandescent bulb light.  The washable baffle/filter is great - I mean, the other one could be washed, but not as easily.  While I already had a vented area for installing this range hood, I do think it's extremely useful to have offered an alternative to cutting holes by giving the option of using a charcoal filter for a ventless option. Sleek and works well - what more could I ask for?  Maybe a price reduction, but hey, who doesn't want more for less?

title: This was a new home/kitchen
text: I have been building a small (not tiny) home for myself.  Paid cash for a small lot, used a fairly simple building method for the house that I could manage more or less by myself and I have been laying aside items for the house as I can - the items that I want like a really nice kitchen vent and a beautiful stainless steel double sink.  I had been waiting and waffling on a stovetop as I wanted an induction style - my second choice was natural/propane gas cooktop as I have always found gas to be so easy to control from keeping things warm to fast, hard boil.  But I am glad I waited and got this induction cooktop - I set it on the counter outside where my summer kitchen will be and tested it - I do love having five burners.  My first time having five!  The fact I can "join" the two side burners so that I can make a grill for steaks or making pancakes is such a nice feature.  Having a completely flat top makes cleanup a breeze and I did purchase a silicone mat to cover the cooktop when not in use to save scratching, pitting...y'know, breakage but it also keeps smears and such off the surface.  Clean it, cover it and it stays clean!  Can't do that with gas burners or traditional electric coil burners either.  If you are in the market to upgrade your kitchen, this is it - for real!

title: Nice, semi-portable pizza oven
text: I set this propane pizza oven up on top of a rectangular heat mat to insure my table did not suffer under the heat from this oven.  I have an 11 pound propane tank - easier size for me to carry - and it hooked up easily enough to this oven.  I ended up keeping an infrared thermometer close to measure the heat and the one thing I would change on this oven.  Having a temperature gauge on top that would show me what the pizza oven's internal temp was would tell me when to put my pizza in - I mean, in my kitchen's electric oven, I set the temp to 450 F and wait for it to "ding" when it has reached that temp before adding my pizza.  So that's why I use the infrared thermometer to know when this oven's internal heat is where I need it to cook my pizza properly.  As far as being portable, this oven is a bit too heavy to say it's really portable, but it can be packed for a camping trip if that's what you want.  All in all, I think this is a good propane pizza oven, but I think it's a bit pricy for what it is.

title: Man, I hated that space between the stove/range and now it's gone (or at least covered)!
text: I have been updating my house and the last thing I did was create a resin counter that is a faux marble (white) style countertop.  This set of white gap covers fits in well with the new countertop and gives my kitchen that smooth, streamlined look - great to cover those gaps!

title: This is a wonderful gas cooktop
text: I vacillated between getting a four burner flat cooktop induction cooktop and a gas cooktop as I have always preferred gas over electric cooktops for the ease of controlling temperatures and when it is turned off, it's off.  Regular electric burners have to cool down which is what I really dislike.  Induction doesn't require the same cool down, but it also requires that all cookware used be compatible.  That's the main reason I went with gas - it is, for me, the most versatile for cooking with whichever pot I may be using. This particular cooktop is EXCELLENT!  This is my first 5-burner cooktop - all my others both electric and gas have only had 4 and it's really cool to have 5 burners.  This one also has a built-in timer which is a great feature when following a recipe that states to let something simmer for say, 10 minutes.  I don't have to look for the timer (in my everything drawer so you know what that's like!) since it's right there on the cooktop.  Very sleek-looking and easy to clean, cooks just perfectly with the ability to dial in the heat you want and when you turn it off, it's off.  That's what makes this perfect for me!  Oh, and while I dropped this into a cooktop opening in my kitchen, this could be placed on a table outside and plugged into an electrical cord as well as hooked to a propane tank for cooking outdoors.  That would make this great for events or just for an outdoor kitchen.  For me, this is the perfect cooktop in my kitchen - glad that I went with it instead of an induction cooktop.

title: I had resisted using gaps
text: And maybe should have gone to a big box store to look at different types/styles of gaps.  These just don't seem to be the best-made items I've ever seen, but they aren't totally flimsy either.  They do fit on both sides of my electric stove, though I think they could be stiffer, sturdier.  All in all, they will work for now.  As I mentioned, I may go to a physical store to examine some other gap products to see if I can find ones more to my liking than these.  They are okay.

title: Live alone in a place with a broken full-size dishwasher
text: Apartments...you see a dishwasher built in and think, woo-hoo, no more washing dishes by hand, right?  I don't have a clue what is wrong with that dishwasher other than it deposits rather greasy white streaks on dishes.  I tried CLR, vinegar, and a few other treatments plus talking to the apartment manager and nothing works or has been done to fix it.  I got this small countertop dishwasher and while it may not be as perfect as having a full-size one that works, it DOES work without leaving white greasy streaks on my dishes.  At least I'm not washing dishes by hand every day - this dishwasher works well for me.  It doesn't hold a great many dishes, but as one person, I don't make a ton of dishes.  I'd say this would be great for an older couple or might be good for an RV.  I am happy not to be doing dishes by hand!

title: Making Kimchee is best done in a separate fridge!
text: Kimchee is really good for you - at least that's my take on it and while others have their own opinions, the main thing is that like some other foods, Kimchee has a distinctive "fragrance" while it is fermenting.  That is the reason for this small fridge.  I didn't want my fresh made yogurt smelling and tasting like Kimchee so it is now ensconced in this small refrigerator, doing its ferment-y thing and not bothering any other foods.  It was actually light enough for me to move around where I had room for it and after plugging it in and allowing several hours to get to a stable temperature, it has a couple of nearly finished Kimchee and tomorrow another couple of jars will be added and a few days after that a couple more - always good to have some at the ready and this fridge is allowing me to do that (and keep the scent separate from other foods).

title: For RV'ers, this is a must!
text: I'm in my 60s and have been contemplating getting an RV, so when I did, I thought about dirty clothes and finding washers and dryers along the way....okay, so this is not a dryer and I did look at the way more expensive dual machines that are also larger and most reviews mentioned how the dryer really has a problem getting clothes dry.  So, back to washing which is the first part of getting clean clothes anyway, right?  This little machine is a power horse for doing the small loads and spinning them to a drip/dry situation.  After that, I have added a couple of lines for drying clothes both inside the RV and the one that is attached outside and the cord attached to a nearby pole/tree.  I don't go through too many clothes at a time and waiting for a sunny day to dry cleaned, washed clothes isn't a problem.  This machine is light weight and easy to stow when not in use.  I would highly recommend it to anyone RVing or other situations where a small, portable washing machine may be a good idea.

title: For use in my RV
text: I have a "short bus" style of RV - y'know, the kind like a truck with a camper on the back, but a little bigger.  Not much, just about the size of the buses for those with disabilities.  It works for me, but the sink really isn't large enough to hold all my dishes after cooking and yes, I do cook most of my meals when I'm out exploring in the RV.  I have actually tried this dishwasher in my house completely hooked up to the faucet with hot water and found that it works great that way should you have problems with your big dishwasher and are waiting for the person to come fix it, this little dishwasher can keep your dishes clean without you having to stand over the sink.  Now, as far as working with this in the RV, I boiled a pot of water outside, added some cool water and then poured this still-hot water into the dishwasher's reservoir and then plugged it in to wash dishes.  It's one more step - to heat the water - but it really wasn't that big a deal since I was set up at my camp spot and had a rocket stove sitting outside the RV.  The rocket stove heats up fast on just a few twigs and holds a good-sized pot easily.  The water boils fast enough and if I'd had a shorter extension cord, I could have had the Gizmo dishwasher next to the rocket stove, its drainage hose in a bucket beneath it.  That may be my normal set up - easier to eat, scrape off the dirty dishes, put them right in the Gizmo and wash right then and there.  But the main thing is, I really like this little dishwasher and I did have my reservations considering the size of my RV and the size of this dishwasher, but after weighing my options (hand wash in a plastic tub because the RV's sink is too small) I figured taking a chance on this machine was worth it.  It was definitely worth it!  Small enough to store when not in use, very portable and able to be used in different ways, this is perfect for on the road!

title: The full size dishwasher in my home quit working
text: I live alone and rent this house.  I have explained to the owner that the dishwasher does not work but they have no interest in buying a new one and having the old one removed and a new one put in just for me.  This came at the perfect time.  I don't mind washing dishes by hand but nobody wants to wash every dish by hand every day forever and ever.  This mini-dishwasher was easy enough to set up on the counter and while it may not wash but a quarter of the dishes a full size dishwasher can do, but considering I don't make a family's amount of dishes in a day, this countertop dishwasher works fine.  It is easy to use and while it makes maybe the same amount of noise as a regular dishwasher, I can't complain about it.  My dishes are clean when they come out of it and the best part is, I didn't have to wash them!  I am thinking of getting a smaller RV to travel in and think this little dishwasher will probably come with me, I like it so much!

title: Induction is a good choice
text: I have both radiant and induction flat cooking surfaces - two burners each - and feel there are pros and cons to both.  This 2-burner induction surface that I received is excellent.  It was a complete kit and all I needed was to have the electrician hook it up before using it.  The fact that this has no knobs and is a completely flat surface is great - nothing to catch food debris at all.  Meaning, this is an easy to clean surface.  A few minutes of saved time in the kitchen is saved time, right!?!  The induction method that does require specific types of pots/pans, that's not a bad thing, but it is one that requires thought and one of the reasons I chose to split my cook surface into two - both radiant and induction.  I may start a ceramic pot on the radiant surface and finish it in the oven.  I do have a couple of radiant heat type cookware that can go from stovetop to oven, but I'm more likely to use something else as the pieces I have that can go into the oven, their lids cannot.  So for all the best ways to cook, I like having choices and this induction cooktop is perfect and will last a long time!

title: I lived on a houseboat for 3 years and used both radiant and induction "twosies"
text: Houseboats - boats in general - require different setups.  Much like RVs, actually.  But the thing about that kind of living is that kitchen areas are small and require that things be moveable/storeable.  To get to the point, I cooked on both radiant and induction plates with two burners each so I did have a full-size stovetop, but they were easier to store when I needed the countertop for other things.  Of the two cooking surfaces, I did find radiant cooktops to be a bit more versatile as induction requires that the utensil have a metal bottom so that the heat reaction would occur.  Not that induction is bad, but it does require more thought in the preparation.  Radiant heat cooktops are the better part of electric cooking - no coils that are exposed, a flat surface that stays that way (I have had a couple of stove tops that one coiled burner was slightly bent up) and is easy to clean.  This surface was fairly easy to install - the electrician was here for right at 30 minutes as I had already removed my traditional oven/stove and replaced it with a Goodwill lower kitchen cabinet.  The back of the cabinet was removed, the top I had already cut to fit this drop in unit and that's exactly what I did and then let the electrician do his part to get this wired.  Now, if you are wondering what I will be doing without an oven that went out the door with the traditional stove, I have a multi-use full size microwave that also air fries, bakes, and broils.  I can fit two full size cookie sheets in my microwave unit and yes, I can cook with metal when using air fry, bake or broil.  Back to the radiant heat cooktop - electrician gone, I had been waiting to try it out and grabbed a smaller skillet, a frozen burger and got to it!  Radiant heat doesn't cook faster or better if that's what you think, but it works great and my burger was finished in a short time.  The burner does take time to cool down, but that's more or less a given with most electric heating.  That is probably the biggest plus of induction over radiant cooking, in how it cools down; however, I am more than pleased with how this radiant heat cooktop is truly and completely flat.  No knobs to turn/twist!  The four burners have a touch-sensitive section in the front to pick which one you want to use and also, two are 1200 watt and two are 1800 watt so you have higher power for stir frying or the like.  One last thing - as I mentioned, I had an electrician wire this cooktop because it had to be tied to a 220 breaker/30 amp load in my home's circuit box.  Being that I'm not comfortable working with electric lines, best to pay someone who knows what they are doing, right?  So, bottom line is, if you are ready to upgrade your kitchen, this radiant heat flat cooktop would be a wonderful addition  to your kitchen.

title: Building a small house for myself
text: I bought a small lot and have approved plans to build a small home for myself which I hope to be finished with the exterior within 6-9 months.  This range hood is scheduled to be put in the kitchen when I get to the interior - I have a double stainless steel undermount sink that will go well with this hood vent that will be above a flat radiant & induction stovetop with a wall mount electric oven.  This is a beautiful range hood with everything needed for me (and my helpers) to install when the time comes and I know it will look elegant in my kitchen.  I guess if there was one wish is that it was a smart vent - I would love to be able to voice control it instead of pushing the buttons when my hands will be messy from cooking.  It would be great to say, "Alexa, turn on the stove vent," when I felt the heat building up.  Just a wish and not a complaint.  This vent is good looking and has everything I need for my new kitchen.

text: Mine is the chef trattoria one and as soon as I received it, I opened and unrolled the picture/magnet.  The directions state to lay it out flat to remove the curl but I didn't need to.  I attached the cop of the picture right under the handle of my dishwasher and gently unrolled and allowed it to adhere to the front of my machine.  At the bottom I did a little smoothing out and it was on.  Looks so cute and really is a "pop" to my kitchen!  What I wish is that they had complimentary sets for say, a dishwasher and refrigerator.  Yeah, I know, fridges come in so many configurations these days - side by side, traditional, freezer on the bottom as well as with or without water and or ice delivery from the front panel.  But after admiring my cool new dishwasher cover, I looked at my fridge and said to it, "you are so plain now!"  What this company has available is really nice and I could see having a few different covers depending on holidays and time of the year.  Neat idea and so easy to change up!

title: Works well for corn and potatoes
text: I just got a sous vide cooker so that I can cook steaks perfectly to my favorite, medium well without the steak ending up tough or chewy.  So having the bagged steak cook a longer time in barely boiling water allows me to "walk away" from cooking.  That being said, at the end of my steak's cook time, I grabbed a frozen corn on the cob and a smaller potato, dropped them both in this container and microwaved them.  After "crisping" my steak, I turned out the corn and potato onto the plate and bam!  Great meal with very little effort!  This container worked well for corn on the cob and a smaller potato.  Next time, I think I will try a good handful of frozen green beans instead of corn and maybe a sweet potato - always worth trying something new!

title: I opened a package of dried cherries and wanted to test this jar
text: The package of dried cherries was resealable, but I needed something to test in this jar.  The cherries have been in this mason jar for about a week now and seem to be just the same as when I opened the pack.  The cherries are still fresh and have a bit of give to them when I chop them up and have that super concentrated cherry flavor.  I do try to keep them in a fairly constant temperature.  I think that can have an effect on how well the jar works.  If I were to change anything about this, I would have the jar tinted.  I have macerated herbs and added them to 100 proof vodka to make tinctures.  While they are "working" on being a finished tincture, I use brown bottles and store them in a shaded, naturally-cool place in my house.  I would think that say, storing herbs you've dried yourself in this jar, preserving the freshness and the green color of the herb would work better in a medium blue or brown bottle.  Other than that, this is a good idea and is working well for my dried cherries.

title: Pizza Peel Is Bad, Pizza Oven Should Be Great With Practice
text:
This is a really nice outdoor pizza oven overall, but it takes some finesse. The unit seems like it's built well and it's a bit sizeable. I wasn't sure if it would need the small camping propane tanks or a full tank, so after reviewing the instructions, I realized a full-sized tank was in order. Thankfully I had one on hand for my grill, so it was an easy switch to get this pizza oven in working order. You will need a full-sized tank.

This thing really gets hot as promised. The temp surpassed the capabilities of my hand-held infrared thermometer (which I expected…some thermometers can read up to 1,000 degrees). I believe this oven does reach the 900-degree range as claimed, which is what you need to achieve great pizzas at home.

Let's talk about the Pizza Peel: This pizza peel doesn't lock in place very well at all! The handle folds down for easy storage, but without it locking in place very well, it doesn't offer the control you need while trying to manipulate the pizzas inside the oven. I plan on getting a better peel for future use. If you order this unit, have another peel on hand so you don't have to use this one.

As a result, getting the pizzas to come out "just right" wasn't easy. I left the heat on the highest setting, but the dough would burn on the outside while remaining doughy on the inside. I turned down the heat, and it would cook more evenly but not get as crispy and golden. There's definitely some fine-tuning to get the perfect pizzas. I think a new peel will help a lot with being able to manipulate the pizzas for a more consistent outcome.

While this oven is a bit sizeable, it's best for occasional entertaining for your family or small groups. If you're planning on making larger pizzas, or need pizzas for a lot of people, this isn't the best option. It's really designed for those small-batch pizzas that yield 4-6 slices. It's also worth mentioning that the name brand, Ooni, is on sale in this price-range, so deciding between this one or that one is personal preference. It's a very good pizza oven with a lot of potential to make great pizzas. I just need to fine-tune a few things and come back with more thoughts.

The Easy Go Washing Wand comes in a small box and in 4 pieces. The washer-part can be connected to any of the 2 extensions or directly to the handle itself for a shorter version or a smaller wash. But with the standard 5 gallon plastic bucket filled with soapy water, which can splash up and be messy, the full assembly keeps you clear of the washing process. It's not hard to push and pull the washer through the clothes, and the wash goes around as you push it down and other parts of the wash load are pushed up. I tried it on a bunch of really dirty, greasy things and in only a minute the water was brown as a sign it was working. The washer-head submerges and vents some of the water you're pushing down into so the clothes get the jet-action of the soapy water going through them. In another 5 gallon bucket filled with the rinse water, the same action with the washer-assembly removes the soapy water. A wringer comes in handy, but the hardest part, which is the agitation of the clothes in the wash-water is taken care of and much simplified by this fantastic plastic washer thing.
